Experiments Overview¶

This section gives an overview of the experiments I performed while/after reading the chapter. All experiments are further down in this Jupyter notebook.

After reading the problem set-up in section 2.1 and before reading about any algorithms, I tried to come up with my own learning algorithm based on statistical t-tests. I implemented the algorithm and compared it to a baseline algorithm that always chooses randomly. I discuss several weaknesses of this approach and listed ideas for further exploration that I did not pursue.

Since section 2.8 on Gradient Ascent methods was specifically mentioned early in the lectures, before reading that section I came up with my own gradient method. It uses a loss function that I later learned is called "regret". I implemented and tested my gradient method.

I also implemented and compared the $\epsilon$-greedy, UCB, and Gradient Ascent methods.

Besides using a 10-armed bandit similar to the book, I also compared all methods using

  1. a bandit whose reward distributions are highly skewed, and
  2. a bandit whose reward distributions change over time. (This ended up being a precursor to the homework, but the homework itself is not included in this notebook.)

Reading Response¶

Questions that I believe will be interesting for further discussion are highlighted in bold.

Skewed reward distributions¶

The book only evaluates with normally distributed rewards. How do the different techniques perform when the reward distribution is extremely skewed?

To get a rough start on answering this question, I evaluated the $\epsilon$-greedy, UCB, and two gradient methods on a 10-armed bandit that gives rewards according to a log-normal distribution. I found that all methods performed poorly relative to a theoretically optimal strategy. The disparity in empirical performance is much larger when the reward distributions are skewed rather than symmetric.

This single experiment is just a start; it is not sufficient to make solid judgements about the techniques.

UCB¶

I really like the UCB idea; I think it is a refinement of what I was trying to get at with the t-test method. I was curious where the exact equation came from, but I found the answer in the supplementary reading by Fischer et al (also referenced in the Bibliographic remarks for section 2.7 in the book).

Real-world examples of bandit problems¶

The multi-armed slot machine example is illustrative, but it isn't interesting. Are bandit problems studied because they are building-blocks for more interesting methods, or are they useful on their own? What are some examples of realistic applications of bandit methods?

The readings are light on application examples. I found only two:

Network routing: The paper by Vermorel and Mohri suggests bandit algorithms can be used to solve the "CDN problem": Given multiple sources for some data, an agent has to decide how to minimize total latency by choosing which sources to connect to. I like this example very much; it is a realistic and clear example of a situation where a bandit method is useful on its own. There are many obvious variants of this exmple, such as a P2P client choosing between multiple peers.

Clinical Trials: The book and papers also give the example of choosing how to allocate patients in a clinitcal trial. I initially thought this example was contrived since there are many, many considerations that go into deciding when to execute a trial vs when to use known procedures. I doubt a clinical trial decision has ever been made based on a bandit algorithm, but I would be interested to be proven wrong.

It turns out that the cited paper is more nuanced and addresses the ethical concerns [Hardwick and Stout 1991]. Once participants are in a study, they can be allocated to treatment or control groups based on a bandit algorithm, with the reward being some measure of patient outcome. The goal of the algorithm is to maximize patient outcomes while still producing enough statistical power to make conclusions about the experimental treatment. Compared to allocating the participants equally between the two groups, the bandit algorithm will hopefully lead to more patients receiving the better treatment. I'm still not sure if there are other considerations in the messy world of clinical trials that would make bandit algorithms unusable, but it is definitely an interesting idea.

A/B testing for software rollouts: This is a new example. DevOps managers could use bandit algorithms to decide which version of code to deploy across a system in a manner similar to the clinical trial example.

This section contains all code and results of the experiments.

Problem Set-up¶

To start, we use the simplest form of the problem: A 2-armed bandit with rewards normally distributed with unknown $\mu$ and $\sigma$.

In [1]:
import numpy as np
    
class Bandit:
    def __init__(self, arms):
        self.rng = np.random.default_rng(0)
        self.arms = arms
        
    def reset(self, seed=0):
        '''
        Call reset() before each experiment to ensure the same sequence 
        of arm pulls will produce the same rewards.
        '''
        self.rng = np.random.default_rng(seed)

    
class NormalBandit(Bandit):
    def __init__(self, mu, sigma):
        '''
        mu: A non-empty array-like of the expected values of rewards for each arm.
        sigma: A non-empty array-like of the standard-deviations of rewards for each arm.
        
        The lengths of mu and sigma much match.
        '''
        super().__init__(np.arange(len(mu)))
        
        if len(mu) != len(sigma):
            raise Exception("Length of `mu` and `sigma` must match.")
            
        if len(mu) == 0:
            raise Exception("`mu` and `sigma` must not be empty.")
        
        self.mu = np.array(mu, dtype=float)
        self.sigma = np.array(sigma, dtype=float)
    
    
    def pull(self, arm_index):
        '''
        Returns a reward after pulling the arm with the given index.
        '''
        return self.rng.normal( self.mu[arm_index], self.sigma[arm_index] )
    

bandit = NormalBandit( [0,1], [1,1] )
bandit.pull(0)

Baseline: Random Strategy¶

We use an agent that pulls the arms randomly as a basline for comparison. We expect it's average reward to converge to 0.5 (the mean reward of the arms).

In [3]:
class FixedExperiment:
    def __init__(self, bandit, total_timesteps):
        self.bandit = bandit
        self.total_timesteps = total_timesteps
        self.timestep = 0
        self.reward = np.empty(total_timesteps)
        self.optimal = np.empty(total_timesteps)
        
    def pull(self, arm):
        t = self.timestep
        
        # Update optimal
        # Must be done before pulling since bandits may change mu as part of pull()
        if arm == np.argmax(bandit.mu):
            self.optimal[t] = 1.0
        else:
            self.optimal[t] = 0.0
        
        # Pull arm and record reward
        r = self.bandit.pull(arm)
        self.reward[t] = r
        
        # Update timestep
        self.timestep += 1
        
        return r

colors = ["$\epsilon$-greedy", "t-test", "ucb", "ga_loss", "ga_book", "optimal", "ga1", "random"]    
    
def plot_experiments(reward, optimal, names):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2)
    
    axs[0].set_ylabel("Average reward\nper timestep")
    axs[0].set_xlabel("Time step")
    for i, data in enumerate(reward):
        axs[0].plot(data, label=names[i], c=f"C{colors.index(names[i])}")

    axs[1].set_ylabel("Proportion of\noptimal choices\nper timestep")
    axs[1].set_xlabel("Time step")
    for i, data in enumerate(optimal):
        axs[1].plot(data, label=names[i], c=f"C{colors.index(names[i])}")
    
    handles, labels = axs[1].get_legend_handles_labels()
    fig.legend(handles, labels)
    
    return fig, axs


def run_random_experiment(__unused__=None, total_timesteps=1000):
    experiment = FixedExperiment(bandit, total_timesteps)
    
    for t in range(total_timesteps):
        experiment.pull(np.random.choice([0,1]))
        
    return experiment


def run_experiment(experiment_function, parameters={}, total_timesteps = 1000, trials = 1000):
    reward = np.zeros(total_timesteps)
    optimal = np.zeros(total_timesteps)

    for t in range(trials): 
        bandit.reset(t)
        experiment = experiment_function(**parameters, total_timesteps=total_timesteps)
        reward += experiment.reward
        optimal += experiment.optimal

    return reward / trials, optimal / trials

def moving_average(a):
    '''
    Calculates a moving average over the array-like `a`.

    return np.cumsum(a, dtype=float) / (np.arange(len(a)) + 1)

First Idea: Statistical t-test¶

My first idea was to alternate pulling each arm until we have a large enough sample size for a t-test to conclude that one arm is better than the other, at which point we switch to always pulling the better arm.

We need to use a Welch's t-test since we do not assume the distributions have equal variance.

In [7]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

def run_ttest_experiment(alpha = 0.05, total_timesteps = 1000):
    ttest_experiment = FixedExperiment(bandit, total_timesteps)

    # Naive implementation using off-the-shelf method. We could implement this as 
    # a constant memory and time if we did the calculations ourselves.
    observations = [[], []]
    best_arm = -1

    for t in range(total_timesteps):

        if best_arm == -1:
            # We haven't found the best arm yet. Need a larger sample.
            arm = t % 2

            reward = ttest_experiment.pull(arm)

            observations[arm].append(reward)

            # Do t-tests when we have an equal number of observations for each arm
            if len(observations[0]) == len(observations[1]):

                _, p_value = ttest_ind(*observations, equal_var=False)

                if p_value < alpha:
                    # We can conclude one of the arms is better
                    best_arm = np.argmax([np.mean(o) for o in observations])

        else:    
            reward = ttest_experiment.pull(best_arm)
    
    return ttest_experiment


ttest_avg_reward, ttest_avg_optimal = run_experiment(run_ttest_experiment)

We will usually find the best lever and converge to the optimal average reward of 1.0, but there is nonzero chance that we will mistakenly think the wrong lever is the best one, and then pull the worst lever forever after!

Because of the way we set up this 2-sided t-test, I don't think the probability of choosing the wrong lever is as high as $\alpha$, and empirical evidence backs up this hunch. Using $\alpha=0.05$, only 6 out of 1000 runs of the t-test algorithm ultimately chose the wrong lever:

Discussion¶

As it is presented here, the t-test method only works for a 2-armed bandit. I see two ways to extend it to work with multi-armed bandits:

  1. Run a tournament to eliminate poor-performing arms. The advantage of this method is it could be used to select the n-best bandit arms rather than just the single best by simply ending the tournament early. The n-best bandit arm problem was addressed in one of the supplementary readings.

  2. We could use another statistical test. There are analogs to the t-test when considering multiple samples.

A more challenging problem would be to modify this approach to work with a non-stationary problem.

Epsilon-greedy methods¶

Here I implement the $\epsilon$-greedy method as presented in the book.

In [10]:
def run_epsilon_greedy_experiment(epsilon = 0.1, total_timesteps=1000):
    experiment = FixedExperiment(bandit, total_timesteps)
    
    values = np.zeros(len(bandit.arms))
    num_pulls = np.zeros(len(bandit.arms))
    for t in range(total_timesteps):
        if np.random.random() < epsilon:
            arm = np.random.choice(bandit.arms)
        else:
            arm = np.argmax(values)
            
        reward = experiment.pull(arm)
        
        num_pulls[arm] += 1
        # Equation 2.3:
        values[arm] = values[arm] + 1 / num_pulls[arm] * (reward - values[arm])
    
    return experiment


epsilon_greedy_avg_reward, epsilon_greedy_avg_optimal = run_experiment(run_epsilon_greedy_experiment)

In the long run, we expect the t-test algorithm to usually perform better than a simple $\epsilon$-greedy algorithm since the t-test will usually pick the optimal arm from some point on. As already mentioned, there is a small chance that the t-test algorithm will have terrible long-run performance. No other algorithm considered here has that flaw.

Upper-Confidence-Bound¶

In [12]:
from math import sqrt, log

def run_ucb_experiment(c = 1, total_timesteps=1000):
    experiment = FixedExperiment(bandit, total_timesteps)
    
    values = np.zeros(len(bandit.arms))
    num_pulls = np.zeros(len(bandit.arms))
    
    for t in range(total_timesteps):    
        try:
            arm = num_pulls.tolist().index(0)
        except ValueError:
            # Equation 2.10
            arm = np.argmax([values[a] + c * sqrt(log(t+1) / num_pulls[a]) for a in bandit.arms])
            
        reward = experiment.pull(arm)
        
        num_pulls[arm] += 1
        
        # Equation 2.3:
        values[arm] = values[arm] + 1 / num_pulls[arm] * (reward - values[arm])
    
    return experiment


ucb_avg_reward, ucb_avg_optimal = run_experiment(run_ucb_experiment)

UCB has several impportant advantages over the t-test method:

  1. It is much easier to extent to a multi-armed bandit.
  2. It does not depend on a normality assumption.

Furthermore, while the t-test method will have usually have optimal long-run performance when its assumptions are satisfied, the UCB method is guaranteed to have very nearly optimal long-run performance under the same assumptions. The UCB method does not have the grave drawback of occasionally converging to the wrong arm. I imagine the t-test method's chance of being very wrong is not worth the risk.

I really like the idea of UCB; it is my favorite method presented in the book. I reserve the right to change my oppinion as I learn more!

Gradient Methods¶

Before reading this section, I came up with two gradient methods of my own.

Idea 1: The probability of choosing an arm is defined as softmax of average sample rewards. As written, this isn't really a gradient algorithm. Rather, it's inspired by gradient descent algorithms I learned the previous day in my Deep Learning class.

This approach is superficially similar to the idea presented in the book since they both rely on sooftmax to create probability distributions. However, my attempt got some important details wrong, and it performed only slightly better than random.

Idea 2: Gradient descent on a loss function. We again define a set of probabilities for pulling each arm, then define the loss as the 2-norm of the vector difference between our current probability distribution and the "Dirac distribution" that always selects the arm with the highest sample average. I later learned that the loss function is sometimes called "regret".

This approach worked as well as the method presented in the book for the 2-armed bandit, the 10-armed bandit, and the 10-armed bandit with skewed reward distributions. It performed substantially worse on the non-stationary bandit. There is no reason to expect it to perform well on a non-stationary bandit since the loss function only makes sense if we assume the reward distribution means do not change over time. It may be possible to modify the loss function to work with non-stationary problems, but I don't see an easy way to do that right now.

Incorrect softmax algorithm¶

In [15]:
def softmax(vals):
    '''
    `vals` must be a numpy array.
    '''
    total = np.sum(np.exp(vals))
    return np.exp(vals) / total


# This strategy doesn't actually work well, so I didn't take the time to make it work 
# for anything other than a 2-armed bandit!
def run_ga1_experiment(total_timesteps=1000):
    experiment = FixedExperiment(bandit, total_timesteps)
    
    values = [0, 0]
    num_pulls = [0, 0]
    thetas = [0.5, 0.5]
    
    for t in range(total_timesteps):    
        arm = np.random.choice([0,1], p=thetas)
        
        reward = experiment.pull(arm)
        
        num_pulls[arm] += 1
        
        # Equation 2.3:
        values[arm] = values[arm] + 1 / num_pulls[arm] * (reward - values[arm])
        
        thetas = softmax(values)
    
    return experiment

Corrected softmax algorithm (from the book)¶

In [16]:
def run_ga_book_experiment(step_size=0.5, total_timesteps=1000):
    experiment = FixedExperiment(bandit, total_timesteps)
    
    probabilities = np.ones(len(bandit.arms)) / len(bandit.arms)
    preferences = np.ones(len(bandit.arms))
    r_bar = 0
    
    for t in range(total_timesteps):    
        arm = np.random.choice(bandit.arms, p=probabilities)
        
        reward = experiment.pull(arm)
        
        # Equation 2.12
        r_bar = t/(t+1)*r_bar + 1/(t+1)*reward 
        for a in bandit.arms:
            if a == arm:
                preferences[a] = preferences[a] + step_size * (reward - r_bar) * (1.0 - probabilities[a])
            else:
                preferences[a] = preferences[a] - step_size * (reward - r_bar) * probabilities[a]
        
        probabilities = softmax(preferences)
    
    return experiment


ga_book_avg_reward, ga_book_avg_optimal = run_experiment(run_ga_book_experiment)

Loss-descent algorithm¶

In [18]:
def run_ga_loss_experiment(step_size=0.05, total_timesteps=1000):
    experiment = FixedExperiment(bandit, total_timesteps)
    
    values = np.zeros(len(bandit.arms))
    num_pulls = np.zeros(len(bandit.arms))
    thetas = np.ones(len(bandit.arms)) / len(bandit.arms)
    
    for t in range(total_timesteps):    
        arm = np.random.choice(bandit.arms, p=thetas)
        
        reward = experiment.pull(arm)
        
        num_pulls[arm] += 1
        
        # Equation 2.3:
        values[arm] = values[arm] + 1 / num_pulls[arm] * (reward - values[arm])
        
        theta_star = np.zeros(len(bandit.arms))
        theta_star[np.argmax(values)] = 1.0
        
        # Take as step in the direction of the gradient
        thetas += step_size * 2 * (theta_star - thetas)
        # Clip and normalize Normalize
        thetas = np.clip(thetas, 0, 1)
        thetas /= thetas.sum()
    
    return experiment

ga_loss_avg_reward, ga_loss_avg_optimal = run_experiment(run_ga_loss_experiment)

# Parameter Study

parameters = [1/128, 1/64, 1/32, 1/16, 1/8, 1/4, 1/2, 1, 2, 4]

def parameter_study(trials = 100, total_timesteps = 1000, exclude_ttest=False, start_i=0):
    
    experiments = {
        "epsilon_greedy": np.empty(len(parameters)),
        "ucb": np.empty(len(parameters)),
        "ga_book": np.empty(len(parameters)),
        "ga_loss": np.empty(len(parameters)),
        "optimal": np.empty(len(parameters)),
    }
    
    if not exclude_ttest:
        experiments["ttest"] = np.empty(len(parameters))
    
    for p, param in enumerate(parameters):
        print("running p =", p)
        
        if not exclude_ttest:
            experiments["ttest"][p] = run_experiment(
                run_ttest_experiment, {"alpha": param}, 
                total_timesteps=total_timesteps, trials=trials)[0][start_i:].mean()

        experiments["epsilon_greedy"][p] = run_experiment(
            run_epsilon_greedy_experiment, {"epsilon": param}, 
            total_timesteps=total_timesteps, trials=trials)[0][start_i:].mean()

        experiments["ucb"][p] = run_experiment(
            run_ucb_experiment, {"c": param}, 
            total_timesteps=total_timesteps, trials=trials)[0][start_i:].mean()

        experiments["ga_book"][p] = run_experiment(
            run_ga_book_experiment, {"step_size": param}, 
            total_timesteps=total_timesteps, trials=trials)[0][start_i:].mean()

        experiments["ga_loss"][p] = run_experiment(
            run_ga_loss_experiment, {"step_size": param}, 
            total_timesteps=total_timesteps, trials=trials)[0][start_i:].mean()
        
        experiments["optimal"][p] = run_experiment(
            run_optimal_experiment, {}, 
            total_timesteps=total_timesteps, trials=trials)[0][start_i:].mean()
    
    return experiments

Highly skewed rewards¶

In [27]:
class LognormalBandit(Bandit):
    
    def __init__(self, mu, sigma):
        '''
        mu: A non-empty array-like of the expected values of rewards for each arm.
        sigma: A non-empty array-like of the standard-deviations of rewards for each arm.
        
        The lengths of mu and sigma much match.
        '''
        super().__init__(np.arange(len(mu)))
        
        if len(mu) != len(sigma):
            raise Exception("Length of `mu` and `sigma` must match.")
            
        if len(mu) == 0:
            raise Exception("`mu` and `sigma` must not be empty.")
        
        self.mu = np.array(mu, dtype=float)
        self.sigma = np.array(sigma, dtype=float)
        
    
    def pull(self, arm_index):
        '''
        Returns a reward after pulling the arm with the given index.
        '''
        return self.rng.lognormal( self.mu[arm_index], self.sigma[arm_index] )

Compared to normally-distributed rewards, there is not much difference between the performance of the methods relative to one another. The UCB method still performs the best and has a large range of useful parameter values. The gradient methods perform similarly for their respective best parameters, and $\epsilon$-greedy is still competitive but doesn't perform quite as well.

One interesting difference is none of the methods perform nearly as well with respect to a theoretically optimal strategy. In the normal case, many methods could find the best arm within 1000 timesteps, while all the methods struggle when the reward distributions are highly skewed. This suggests that there may be room for improvement for highly-skewed reward distributions.

Non-stationary rewards¶

This section explores performance when the reward distributions change over time.

The question posed in the homework is not included here. I did not explore the affect of using a constant step-size when updating sample averages.

In [33]:
# Uses parameters from exercise 5
class NonstationaryNormalBandit(Bandit):
    
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__(np.arange(10))
        self.mu = np.zeros(10, dtype=float)
    
    def pull(self, arm_index):
        '''
        Returns a reward after pulling the arm with the given index.
        '''
        reward = self.rng.normal( self.mu[arm_index], 1.0 )
        
        self.mu += self.rng.normal( 0.0, 0.01, 10 )
        
        return reward
    
    def reset(self, seed):
        # We also need to reset the mu's
        super().reset(seed)
        self.mu = np.zeros(10, dtype=float)

    
bandit = NonstationaryNormalBandit()

When we look at a single run, we can see when the UCB and $\epsilon$-greedy methods are able to find the best arm, and how long it takes them to realize there is a new best arm. As time goes on, it takes longer and longer for the methods to switch to the new best arm. This problem may be partially addressed by using constant step-size when computing sample averages
